Celebrating the arrival of spring in the Yukon! Nothing beats the feeling of being near the flowing water after a long winter. As the snow melts away, we can finally feel the warmth of the sun on our skin again. The blue sky and majestic mountains in the distance make the scenery even more breathtaking. What's your favorite thing about spring?

With the snow melting, the lower elevation routes are slowly starting to melt. The first one to do so is usually Slims River, located in Kluane National Park and Reserve. It is a fairly flat hike, which brings you right at the front of the Kaskawulsh Glacier... One of the most amazing landscape in the Yukon in my opinion. This was quite a long hike for a first hike of a season as it totaled 65 kilometers but with no elevation and the amazing views as motivation, it went fairly well! It is now possible to loop the two hikes together as there is no water flowing at the end of this valley, it is very nice to be able to come back the other way, even though a bit sad to see the glacier melting and the water changing course.
